y's "public enemy" to John Wayne's "quiet man" in the process. Whether as figures of Depression-era social disruption, avatars of presidential patriarchy and national manhood, or allegories of postwar white flight and the nuclear family, Irish American masculinities occupied a distinctive and unrivaled visibility and role in popular American film.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aIrish Americans in motion pictures. 0aMasculinity in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWhite people in motion pictures. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aHistory : Ethnic History. 4aSociology : Ethnicity. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848910040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438489100423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438489100/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles